Besides the changes already mentioned, Latin exhibits several others more rare and accidental. One of these is the change from an adjective or noun to a preposition. An example of this would be secundum, circum, or cause} in Latin, or round and midst in English. The change of a noun, adjective, or pronoun to a conjunction is another transfer. Modo, ciderunt, erum, or quod would represent this in Latin, and English examples would be the pronoun that and the adJective belle.
